<F P=100> East Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnian Serbs Announce Unilateral Peace as Shelling Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bosnian Serbs Announce Unilateral Peace as Shelling Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2004170094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1619 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2004170094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 20 (XINHUA) -- The Bosnian Serb 
Presidential Office today announced a unilateral peace in 
Gorazde to allow U.N. peacekeepers into the city. 
  The announcement came after yesterday's peace agreement 
between Bosnian Serbs and the U.N. peacekeeping force allowing 
the latter to enter Bosnia's eastern city of Gorazde Wednesday 
[19 April] to enable humanitarian organizations to pursue their 
work. 
  This act was in response to statements Tuesday from the 
Russian and U.S. presidents, Boris Yeltsin and Bill Clinton. 
  The Bosnian Serbs also called for the international 
community 
to press the Muslims to accept the cease-fire agreement and hold 
peaceful negotiations to solve the crisis. 
  Foreign press reports said that by the noon Bosnian Serb 
forces continued to shell the besieged Muslim enclave of 
Gorazde, despite their "unilateral peace" announcement. 
  The three-week Serb offensive has killed at least 345 people 
and wounded more than 1,000, the reports added. 

</TEXT>

