<F P=100> Science &amp; Technology </F>
<H3> <TI>   Beijing Sets Up Ground-Based Test System for Space Flights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Beijing Sets Up Ground-Based Test System for Space Flights </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1804115694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0742 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1804115694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 18 (XINHUA) -- China has established 
a ground-based test system for space flights, paving the way for 
the further development of the country's aerospace industry. 
  The various kinds of ground test facilities and devices that 
have gone into operation make it possible to carry out any 
conventional or routine test on satellites and rockets on the 
ground. 
  Wind tunnels provide test results at different stages of 
rocket launching while large-sized heat-testing devices ranging 
from one m to seven m in diameter allow simulations for 
satellite flights in outer space and in different temperatures. 
  China has also built a gigantic rocket testing launch pad 
which is 59 m high, 41 m long and about 22 m in width, providing 
a large amount of test data for rocket engine system designs. 
  In addition, it has also built a huge centrifugal machine 
and 
vibration test tower, both controlled by modern computers. 

</TEXT>

