<F P=100> Science &amp; Technology </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commission: Beijing Considering Setting Up High-Tech Fund </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commission: Beijing Considering Setting Up High-Tech Fund </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1804120594 Beijing XINHUA in English 0743 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1804120594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 18 (XINHUA) -- China is considering 
setting up a high-tech investment foundation in cooperation with 
foreign financial bodies. 
  The total sum will be 120 million U.S. dollars, the State 
Science and Technology Commission revealed today. 
  "China develops high technologies mainly on its own 
strength, 
but it also welcomes assistance from abroad," said Huang Qitao, 
deputy director of the commission. 
  The country started building its high-tech industry in 1988, 
under the "torch plan". Last year there were more than 10,000 
high-tech firms nationwide, with 700,000 workers. 
  Among them, 4,000 are overseas-funded companies. 
  Domestic sales and exports of high-tech products will make 
up 
25 percent of China's gross national product and export volume 
by the year 2000, according to the government blueprint. 
  The new materials, energy, biological technology, 
electronics 
and information industries, and environmental protection are 
highlights on China's high-tech plan. 

</TEXT>

