<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Center `Will Not Relax' Control of Money Supply </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Center `Will Not Relax' Control of Money Supply </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2004131194 Beijing XINHUA in English 1247 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2004131194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, April 20 (XINHUA) -- China's central bank 
will not relax its control of the money supply in view of the 
slower rate of growth of some state-owned enterprises, a senior 
bank official said here today. 
  Dai Xianglong, vice-governor of the People's Bank of China, 
noted that in the first quarter of this year, state-owned 
enterprises recorded a production growth of only two percent, in 
contrast to 50 percent for township enterprises and 90 percent 
for foreign-funded ones. 
  According to the State Statistical Bureau, the country's 
overall economic growth was 12.6 percent for the January-March 
period. 
  Factors contributing to the slow growth of state-owned 
enterprises include tightened investment in fixed assets and 
reduced supply of materials, said Dai, now attending a national 
conference here in China's largest city. 
  Another factor was that state-owned enterprises which have 
been transformed into stockholding or joint venture companies 
ceased to have their production included in the state sector's 
statistics. 
  The state increased loans for working capital to 
enterprises. 
From now on, said Dai, banks will act on a case-to-case basis in 
extending loans to state-owned enterprises. 
  Priority will be given to those with good economic 
performance, followed by those in a position to turn red into 
black in a short time. 
  Enterprises up to the neck in debt and with no hope of 
recovery will be declared bankrupt, in line with the "bankruptcy 
law," Dai added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-3452 </DOCNO>
