<H3> <TI>   Jiang Zemin Inspects Telecommunications Center </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jiang Zemin Inspects Telecommunications Center </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2004142694 Beijing XINHUA in English 1345 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2004142694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 20 (XINHUA) -- Chinese President 
Jiang Zemin inspected the Beijing International 
Telecommunications Center here today, urging concerted efforts 
to make telecommunications work better serve the country's 
economic development. 
  Jiang, general secretary of the Central Committee of the 
Chinese Communist Party (CPC), said that the CPC Central 
Committee and the State Council are pleased at the rapid 
development of China's telecommunications services in recent 
years. 
  Situated on the southern side of Beijing Sanyuan fly-over, 
the Beijing international telecommunications center is an 
important link in China's national telecommunications network 
which transmits international telephones, telegraph, and data 
business into or out of China. 
  Jiang arrived at the center this morning, accompanied by 
Chen 
Xitong, party secretary of Beijing, and Wu Jichuan, minister of 
posts and telecommunications. 
  At a TV conference room, he talked by video telephone with 
the head of Shanghai Telecommunications Bureau -- about supplies 
of vegetables, traffic conditions and development of 
telecommunications in Shanghai. 
  Jiang urged Shanghai and Beijing telecommunications bureaux 
to learn from and compete with each other. 
  At the international telephone control room, he urged the 
operators to devote efforts to their study of foreign languages. 
  In a meeting room, Jiang listened to a report from Beijing 
telecommunications bureau and the Ministry of Posts and 
Telecommunications. 
  He said that the establishment of a socialist market 
economic 
structure demands a highly developed telecommunications network. 
  He called on various departments within telecommunications 
and posts services to enhance cooperation and use state 
investment to its best advantage. 

</TEXT>

