<H3> <TI>   China To Become `Most Competitive Nation' by 2010 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    China To Become `Most Competitive Nation' by 2010 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2104034794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0339 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2104034794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, April 20 (XINHUA) -- China will become the 
most competitive nation in the world by 2010, according to a 
survey published here today. 
  The survey of some 1,700 entrepreneurs across the world was 
jointly conducted by the World Economic Forum and the 
International Institute of Management Development for an annual 
report on the competitiveness of world countries. 
  China ranks first in competitiveness by 2010, followed by 
the 
United States, Japan, Germany, South Korea and Singapore, 
according to the survey. 
  The U.S., Japan and Singapore are ahead of others for the 
stress they put on their competitiveness. 
  According to the 1993 report, the ranking in competitiveness 
is as follows: Japan, the United States, Denmark, Switzerland, 
Germany, the Netherlands, Austria, New Zealand, Sweden and 
Belgium. 

</TEXT>

