<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   International Group To Provide Petrochemical Loan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    International Group To Provide Petrochemical Loan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2004135294 Beijing XINHUA in English 1258 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2004135294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 20 (XINHUA) -- An international 
syndicate consisting of six foreign banks and a Chinese bank 
will provide a loan of 36 million U.S. dollars for a project to 
manufacture polypropylene in China. 
  The loan is being made by the China Dalian West Pacific 
Petrochemical Company (WEPEC), a joint-venture of China, France 
and Hong Kong. 
  The agreement was signed at the Great Hall of the People 
here 
today. 
  WEPEC, the largest Sino-foreign joint venture in China's 
petrochemical field, will use the loan to bring in Italian 
equipment and technology for the manufacture of polypropylene. 
  WEPEC, established in 1990 with a total investment of 800 
million U.S. dollars, is one of the key projects for China's 
eighth five-year plan period (1990-1995). 
  The loan was arranged and lead-managed by the Shanghai 
branch 
of the ABN Amro Bank of the Netherlands. Other participants 
include banks from Australia, Germany, Singapore, Italy, the 
Middle East and the Shanghai Pudong Development Bank of China. 
  Among those present at today's signing ceremony were Gu 
Xiulian, China's minister of chemical industry, D.J. Van Houten, 
Dutch ambassador to China, and Igno van Waesberghe, regional 
manager for North East Asia of ABN Amro Bank. 

</TEXT>

