<F P=100> North Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Inner Mongolia Expands Radio, TV Network </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Inner Mongolia Expands Radio, TV Network </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2104112294 Beijing XINHUA in English 0740 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2104112294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hohhot, April 21 (XINHUA) -- An expanding radio and 
TV network has brought a more colorful and better informed life 
to herdsmen in Alxa League in the remote western part of the 
Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, according to local officials. 
  The officials said radio broadcasts now reach 80 percent of 
the league's population, and TV programs 75 percent. 
  With an area of 270,000 sq km, mostly desert, the league's 
major transportation means used to be camels and horses. So the 
herdsmen lived an isolated life until the early 1980s. 
  Since then, the league authorities have invested 50 million 
yuan building 38 relay stations and 49 satellite ground 
stations, bringing 14 TV channels to the local people. 
  According to the officials, some small towns and villages 
have even set up their own cable TV networks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

