<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interest in Mainland Travel Cools </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Interest in Mainland Travel Cools </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2104090594 Taipei CNA in English 0809 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2104090594 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Y. C. Tsai] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, April 21 (CNA) -- Taiwan interest in 
visiting Mainland China substantially cooled in February and is 
expected to remain low in the wake of the March 31 robbery and 
murder of 24 Taiwan tourists while on a pleasure cruise of 
Qiandao Lake, the cabinet-level Mainland Affairs Council (MAC) 
said Thursday [21 April]. 
  Council statistics show that the number of Taiwan residents 
who applied for a "Taiwan Compatriot Certificate" to enter the 
mainland totaled 80,000 in February, down 31.62 percent from the 
year-earlier level. 
  MAC officials said that Taiwan residents have made more than 
6.12 million visits to the mainland since a Taiwan Government 
ban was lifted in November 1987. 
  People here were prohibited from visiting the mainland since 
the Kuomintang Government moved to Taiwan in 1949 after losing a 
civil war to the Chinese Communists. 
  Currently, Taiwan residents must apply to mainland 
authorities in Hong Kong for the certificate to enter the 
mainland. 
  The officials noted that mainland travel is expected to 
remain lackluster as Taiwan residents have been enraged by 
Beijing's callous handling of the Qiandao Lake murders and the 
local tourist industry has launched a drive to boycott tours to 
the mainland. 

</TEXT>

