<H3> <TI>   Taipei, EBRD Agree on Loans to East Europe </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Taipei, EBRD Agree on Loans to East Europe </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2004084994 Taipei CNA in English 0727 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2004084994 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Y.C. Tsai] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, April 20 (CNA) -- Taiwan will work together 
with a European bank to strengthen ties with East European 
countries, the International Economic Cooperation Development 
Fund under the Ministry of Economic Affairs announced Wednesday 
[20 April]. 
  A spokesman for the fund said that a memorandum of 
understanding (MOU) between Taiwan and the European Bank for 
Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) was signed in St. 
Petersburg, Russia Tuesday [19 April] during the bank's third 
annual meeting. 
  Taiwan Representative in Belgium Lu Chao-chung and Bank 
President Jacques de Larosiere inked the MOU, under which the 
fund pledges to earmark U.S.$20 million to help finance economic 
reform projects in East European countries, he noted. 
  Both sides agreed to the cooperative ties in February when 
Governor Samuel Shieh of the Central Bank of China met with de 
Laros in Paris, he added. 
  The first loan project will go to an airport navigation 
system in Riga, Latvia, he pointed out. 
  The spokesman pledged that the fund will provide more 
financial assistance to East European countries in line with the 
government's strategy to promote cooperation with that part of 
the world. 
  Established in 1988, the fund plays a key role in supplying 
financial and technical assistance to developing countries 
friendly to Taiwan. 

</TEXT>

