<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Political Party Set Up in Hong Kong </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Political Party Set Up in Hong Kong </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2004165694 Beijing XINHUA in English 1432 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2004165694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hong Kong, April 20 (XINHUA) -- A new political 
organization - the Hong Kong Progressive Alliance - came into 
being here today. 
  Five convenors of the Alliance Yu Sun Say, Ambrose Lau Hon 
Chuen, Fanny Lai Ip Po Ping, Carson Wen and Au Yeung Sing Shiu 
jointly made the announcement at a press conference here this 
afternoon. 
  The organizing committee of the Alliance, comprising 52 Hong 
Kong businessmen and professionals, is ready to admit founding 
members and plans to take part in the 1994 and 1995 elections at 
all levels in the territory. 
  Ambrose Lau Hon Chuen said after 1997, China will implement 
the policy of "one country, two systems" in the Hong Kong 
Special Adminstrative Region which will then be governed by the 
Hong Kong people with a high degree of autonomy. 
  "The committee believes that those who wish to stay in Hong 
Kong and take part in the building of the territory's future 
should organize themselves to participate in political 
activities to ensure the effective implementation of the 
said-policies and a smooth transition, and to maintain the 
stability and prosperity of Hong Kong," Lau said. 
  He noted that the Alliance advocates the importance of 
building a good relationship between Hong Kong and the Chinese 
Mainland and to create a stable environment for businessmen to 
invest in Hong Kong. 
  Lau stated that his organization promotes communication with 
the mainland, and intends to adopt an open and positive attitude 
in giving constructive views to the Chinese leaders on matters 
relating to Hong Kong. 
  The alliance supports the development of a democratic 
government, but takes a pragmatic approach and gives due 
consideration to the historical situation, lau said, adding it 
believes that democratic development should follow the 
principles of even participation and orderly progress, so as not 
to unduly disrupt the harmony and stability of the society. 
  In another development, two other organizations - the United 
Democrats of Hong Kong and meeting point - announced on Monday 
[18 April] that they would merge to form a single party - the 
Democratic Party in Hong Kong in October. 

</TEXT>

