Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taipei Proposes Qiandao Disaster Talks Schedule </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Taipei Proposes Qiandao Disaster Talks Schedule </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2004131894 Taipei CNA in English 1241 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2004131894 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Soifa Wu] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, April 20 (CNA) -- The Straits Exchange 
Foundation (SEF) faxed a message to its mainland Chinese 
counterpart Wednesday [20 April] suggesting that a special round 
of talks be held in Hong Kong April 27-29 on issues related to 
the March 31 Qiandao Lake travel disaster, in which 24 Taiwan 
tourists died. 
  "We hope Beijing's Association for Relations Across the 
Taiwan Strait (ARATS) will give US a definite answer soon," SEF 
Secretary- General Chiao Jen-ho said. 
  It was the second time in less than half a month SEF 
expressed its intention to talk with ARATS about the Qiandao 
Lake incident. ARATS failed to reply to a similar request made 
last week. 
  Chiao reaffirmed that the talks will focus on possible 
compensation for the bereaved families of the incident's victims 
as well as the protection of Taiwan tourists and businessmen in 
Mainland China. 
  He again urged Beijing authorities to thoroughly investigate 
the incident, to make public the results of the investigation, 
and to respond to 10 unanswered questions of the families, 
including why autopsies were performed on the victims' bodies 
without the prior approval of their relatives. 
  "Although ARATS has informed US that mainland authorities 
have already arrested three suspects involved in the incident, 
the message was too simple to settle our doubts and 
apprehensions," Chiao noted. 
  Beijing's handling of the incident angered not only the 
bereaved families but also the general public and government 
authorities here. Local travel agencies have decided to stop 
organizing tour groups to the mainland from May 1. 
Government-sponsored cultural exchanges with the mainland have 
also been suspended. 
  Chiao said that unless Beijing opens up about the matter in 
detail and handles all related issues properly, cross-Strait 
relations would be adversely affected. 
  SEF and ARATS are semi-official organizations founded by 
their respective governments to handle cross-Strait exchanges in 
the absence of official ties. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

