<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesperson on UK Parliament Report, Qiandao Lake Incident </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesperson on UK Parliament Report, Qiandao Lake Incident </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK2204053294 Beijing CHINA DAILY in English 22 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> HK2204053294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing CHINA DAILY </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By staff reporter Xu Yang: "Foreign Ministry Blasts HK </F>
Report"] 
  [Text] A foreign ministry spokesman yesterday attacked a 
recent report on Hong Kong by Britain's House of Commons Foreign 
Affairs Committee. 
  The conclusion of the committee's lengthy report runs 
totally 
counter to Britain's professed desire to improve relations with 
China Wu Jianmin told a weekly news briefing in Beijing. 
  The report persists in supporting the "erroneous" policy of 
the British Government on the Hong Kong election issue and its 
"continued" confrontations with China, Wu said. 
  The report had fully revealed Britain's intention to 
"prolong 
its colonial influence in Hong Kong." 
  However China has the resolve and capacity to maintain 
stability and prosperity in Hong Kong long after it returns to 
China in 1997 he said. 
  Wu also discussed the Qiandao Lake accident in which 32 
people, including 24 Taiwanese tourists, died on a blazing 
cruise boat on March 31. 
  He said the mainland side hoped the tragedy would not hinder 
the further development of exchanges across the Taiwan Straits. 
  The case has been confirmed as murder and three men in their 
twenties have been arrested. 
  Wu said representatives from the mainland's Association for 
Relations Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS) and Taiwan's Straits 
Exchange Foundation (SEF) are expected to meet next month to 
discuss ways to protect people and property on both sides. But 
he did not say where the meeting will be convened. 
  Top figures from ARATS and SEF will also do their utmost to 
ease the effects of this unfortunate accident, Wu said. 
  He went on to back China's oil deployment efforts in the 
Nansha Islands and their waters, saying it was entirely within 
China's sovereignty. 

</TEXT>

