<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Call For Immediate Cease-Fire Throughout Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbs Call For Immediate Cease-Fire Throughout Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2204053394 Beijing XINHUA in English 0339 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2204053394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 21 (XINHUA) -- Bosnian Serb leader 
Radovan Karadzic today proposed a complete cease-fire and 
disengagement of forces in Bosnia to make the entire Bosnia a 
UN- designated safe area and thus create conditions for peace 
talks. 
  A complete halt to hostility is the only way out for the 
Bosnia crisis, as only cease-fire can lead to a political 
settlement and end the Bosnia war, Karadzic said in letters to 
the five permanent members of the UN Security Council. 
  He pointed out that the Serb proposal is aimed at securing 
peace in the former Yugoslav republic, adding that it is now the 
best time for resolving the Bosnia crisis once and for all. 
  Serbs have announced unilateral cease-fire, but Muslims do 
not intend to do the same, the Serb leader noted. 
  Karadzic stressed that the attempt of the international 
community to realize a military balance on the Bosnian 
battlefield could reach nowhere but to prolong the war, and so 
would the new plan proposed by the United States, which he 
described as "completely wrong." 
  U.S. President Bill Clinton announced on Wednesday three 
steps which he said would help reach a negotiated settlement in 
Bosnia. The steps include extending NATO air strike threats 
against Serbs to UN-declared safe areas to halt Serb attacks, 
tightening economic sanctions on Serbia and supporting UN 
humanitarian aid to the Muslim enclave of Gorazde and more UN 
peacekeepers in Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-3534 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi078_a_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-078 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Boris Yeltsin, President Clinton Discuss Bosnian Crisis </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Boris Yeltsin, President Clinton Discuss Bosnian Crisis </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2104195994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1823 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2104195994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, April 21 (XINHUA) -- A spokesman for Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin announced here today that the Russian, 
U.S. presidents and representatives from United Nations and 
European Union will probably meet within a month over the 
Bosnian crisis. 
  Yeltsin's press secretary Vyacheslav Kostikov made the 
announcement at a press conference in the Kremlin today. 
  According to Kostikov, President Yeltsin talked with U.S. 
President Bill Clinton for 40 minutes over telephone late last 
night. 
  He said President Yeltsin firmly opposes NATO air strikes at 
the Bosnian Serb Forces without consulting with Russia. 
  Kostikov added that President Clinton had promised to act 
with caution in dealing with such matters in the future. 
  Yeltsin on Tuesday [19 April] called on the Serbs to 
withdraw 
from around the Muslim enclave of Gorazde, Eastern Bosnia, to 
allow the deployment of U.N. Peacekeepers. 

</TEXT>

