<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   South Korea, U.S. May Hold `Team Spirit' Exercise in Nov </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    South Korea, U.S. May Hold `Team Spirit' Exercise in Nov </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2104142894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1352 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2104142894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 21 (XINHUA) -- South Korea and the 
United States will conduct this year's "Team Spirit" joint 
military exercise in November if Pyongyang continues to reject 
additional nuclear inspection and the resumption of inter-Korean 
dialogue. 
  This was announced after a meeting between visiting U.S. 
Defense Secretary William Perry and his South Korean counterpart 
Yi Pyong-tae here Wednesday [20 April]. 
  Perry, who delayed his visit to Seoul due to last week's 
downing of U.S. Army helicopters by friendly fire in Iraq, 
arrived here late Tuesday night. 
  The two defense ministers focused on the nuclear issue in 
the 
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK). They decided to 
hold the "Team Spirit" exercise if no progress is made on the 
issue by the end of October. 
  They believe that the deployment of Patriot missiles at 
American military bases in South Korea will contribute to 
deterring war. 
  They agreed, however, that there are no particular signs of 
military confrontation at present. 
  The "Team Spirit" joint military exercise had been held 
annually since 1976, but was cancelled for the first time in 
1992 when the DPRK signed the nuclear safeguards accord with the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA). 
  The exercise was revived last year after a stalemate in 
inter- Korean talks over nuclear inspections. 
  The first shipment of Patriot missiles and their launchers 
arrived in South Korea Monday aboard two U.S. military transport 
ships. 
  South Korea and the U.S. claimed that the Patriots are 
purely 
defensive missiles designed to counter air strikes and SCUD 
missiles. 
  But the DPRK said that the missiles are designed for 
offensive purposes, while describing the "Team Spirit" as a 
"rehearsal for invading the DPRK." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

