<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   Report on U.S. Investigation of Downed Helicopters </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Report on U.S. Investigation of Downed Helicopters </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2104190894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1503 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2104190894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, April 21 (XINHUA) -- U.S. Defense 
Department investigators have found that the IFF (identification 
friend or foe) systems of the two U.S. Army helicopters shot 
down by U.S. fighter planes were turned off when the incident 
took place, it was reported here today. 
  The two U.S. UH-60A Black Hawk helicopters mistakenly 
identified as Iraqi Hind helicopters by the two U.S. Air force 
F-15C fighters were shot down in northern Iraq on April 14. 
  The WASHINGTON TIMES quoted Pentagon officials as saying 
that 
the switches on the Black Hawks' IFF units were found in the 
"off" position when investigators sifted through the wreckage in 
the crash sites. 
  But one official described the findings as preliminary, 
saying the crashes' impact might have jarred the switches from 
"on" to "off." 
  The newspaper said if the helicopters had been flying 
through 
the no-fly zone with the IFF transponder shut off, it would 
explain why AWACS [airborne warning and control system] aircraft 
got no response when it electronically queried them shortly 
before the F- 15C planes fired the missiles. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

