<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ziang, Li, Qiao Send Messages Supporting Orphan Campaign </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ziang, Li, Qiao Send Messages Supporting Orphan Campaign </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2104192594 Beijing XINHUA in English 1516 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2104192594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 21 (XINHUA) -- The Chinese campaign 
to help orphans and if possible adopt them has aroused wide 
attention among people of all walks of life since it was 
initiated late last year. 
  The Ministry of Civil Affairs, the Ministry of Radio, Film 
and Television and the Ministry of Culture will jointly hold a 
large show and a charity auction in a bid to raise more funds 
for orphans. 
  A group of well-known cultural and artistic workers, and 
business people have volunteered to join "Songs for Orphans", a 
fund-raising program launched by the Beijing Music Radio Station. 
  More and more people are taking part in the publicity 
campaign, which has also won great support from many overseas 
Chinese. 
  Chinese President Jiang Zemin, Premier Li Peng and Chairman 
of the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress Qiao 
Shi have recently each sent personal messages of support to the 
campaign. 
  China is believed to have about 100,000 orphans. But living 
standards of orphans are below the national per capita average. 
  Orphans now living in various welfare organizations across 
the country only have an average monthly living expense of 50 
yuan. 
  The helping-the-orphan program was initiated by the China 
Society for the Promotion of Social Services, under the guidance 
of the Ministry of Civil Affairs. 
  The program is aimed at pooling more funds and other 
resources to help orphans live a better life, resume study, to 
help upgrade endangered buildings in welfare centers and to buy 
more medical equipment for welfare facilities. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

