<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   National Legal Conference on Market Economy Laws </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    National Legal Conference on Market Economy Laws </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2104141294 Beijing XINHUA in English 1325 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2104141294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Haikou, April 21 (XINHUA) -- Chinese departments of 
industry and commerce have formulated new laws and regulations 
to facilitate the creation of a market economy nationwide. 
  A number of new laws and regulations were formulated in 1993 
to maintain market order, according to delegates to a national 
conference on the legal system, which opened here today. 
  These include the Law Against Unfair Competition and the Law 
on the Protection of Consumers' Interests and Rights. 
  Delegates said that in 1993 local departments of industry 
and 
commerce formulated rules for regulating advertising, another 
set of regulations regarding the registration and management of 
commodity markets, and still another set of regulations 
governing punishment of smugglers. 
  Furthermore, departments of industry and commerce in Fujian, 
Guangdong and Shanxi provinces and in the big cities of Qingdao 
and Shenyang published rules for regulating the activities of 
brokers. 
  Also in 1993, the departments in Jiangsu Province and 
Beijing 
formulated a set of regulations on the management and 
registration of joint stock companies; the Gansu provincial 
administration of industry and commerce published a set of 
provisional regulations concerning auctions; and the Hainan 
Provincial administration of industry and commerce formulated a 
set of regulations regarding the registration of enterprises' 
legal status and another set of regulations against unfair 
competition. 
  The departments in Jilin Province and big cities of Tianjin, 
Xiamen, Shenzhen, Shenyang, Xian and Zhuhai have abolished or 
revised existing regulations that are in conflict with the needs 
of building a market economy, they said. 
  Local departments also formulated regulations and rules to 
improve supervision of law enforcement by their staff, delegates 
said. 
  The Tianjin municipal administration of industry and 
commerce 
and the Dalian city administration of industry and commerce 
published a set of regulations on the initiative-based 
responsibility system for their staff and another set of 
regulations concerning the punishment of rule-breaking staff 
members. 
  Delegates said that departments of industry and commerce in 
all the provinces and regions except Inner Mongolia and Tibet 
have set up offices in charge of formulating regulations and 
rules. 
  To date, 184 departments at the prefectural level and 528 
departments at the county level have set up such offices, they 
added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

