<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pudong To Establish Bonded Textile Trading Center </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pudong To Establish Bonded Textile Trading Center </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2204111994 Beijing XINHUA in English 0920 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2204111994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, April 22 (XINHUA) -- China's first bonded 
textile trading center will be established in the Waigaoqiao 
bonded zone in the eastern sector of the Pudong New Area in 
Shanghai. 
  This was stated here today by Wu Wenying, the president of 
the China National Textile Council. 
  The trading center will be located in Huayuan International 
Mansion, whose foundation was laid today, and will include an 
exhibition hall, a spot-trade market and bonded warehouses for 
the display and trading of textile machinery and new textile 
products and technologies. 
  As one of China's largest industrial sectors and the 
mainstay 
of its exports, the textile industry has seen closer contacts 
with international markets and faster steps in restructuring 
during recent years, making the establishment of a national free 
trade market a necessity, according to Wu Wenying. 
  The president also explained that Shanghai, as the country's 
largest economic center and number one trading port, and blessed 
with China's largest free trade zone in Waigaoqiao, has been 
chosen to take on the task. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-3582 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi078_n_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-078 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Automobile Market Chain To Be Set Up in Beijing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Automobile Market Chain To Be Set Up in Beijing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2104114694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0740 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2104114694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Yinchuan, April 21 (XINHUA) -- China will set up an 
automobile market chain in Beijing next month. 
  Preparations started in October 1993, and the chain went 
into 
trial operation last February in this capital city of Ningxia 
Hui Autonomous Region. 
  Preparations are underway to move the headquarters of the 
chain from Yinchuan to Beijing. Meanwhile, the Beijing Asian 
and Pacific Auto Market Town is expected to open May 26. 
  The first meeting of members of the chain is to be held in 
June. 
  Guo Jiyuan, director of the Preparatory Committee for the 
auto market chain, said that its establishment is aimed at 
building an auto sales network nationwide. 
  Guo said efforts will be made to build wholesale centers in 
major auto manufacturing and distributing areas, and to bring 
along a retail sales network in the surrounding areas. 
  So far, more than 1,000 auto manufacturers, salesmen and 
customers have showed their willingness to join the market 
chain, and 110 have already signed up. 
  With the improvement of the people's living standards there 
has been a growing demand for automobiles in China. 
  Statistics show that China's automobile market is as large 
as 
one million units a year, with 80 percent domestically produced 
and 20 percent imported. 
  Annual sales of autos will reach two million by the year 
2000, Guo predicted. 
  In the beginning of this year the Ministry of Machine 
Industry announced 1994's plan for the auto industry, saying 1.3 
million automobiles will be produced. 
  The auto industry, as one of the backbone industries in 
China, has registered high growth in recent years. In 1993 
China produced 1.18 million automobiles, an increase of 20 
percent over 1992. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

