<H3> <TI>   Guangdong To Build Highway With Malaysian Funds </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Guangdong To Build Highway With Malaysian Funds </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2104192994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1535 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2104192994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Guangzhou, April 21 (XINHUA) -- A contract for a new 
express highway to be jointly built by China and Malaysia, that 
will link Yangjiang with Zhanjiang in south China's Guangdong 
Province, was signed here today. 
  Its cost is estimated at 6.68 billion yuan, which will be 
raised by two Malaysian companies, the United Engineers 
(Malaysia) Berbhad and the Ho Hup Construction Company Berbhad 
of Malaysia. 
  The 188-kilometer express highway will have four lanes, 
designed for speed up to 120 km per hour. It involves the 
building of 148 bridges and 34 overpasses. 
  The construction of the highway will be started late next 
year and is expected to be completed by 1998. 

