Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government-Consumption Spending Highest in Asia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government-Consumption Spending Highest in Asia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2004172294 Taipei CNA in English 1312 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2004172294 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Flor Wang] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, April 20 (CNA) -- Taiwan's government- 
consumption expenditure accounted for 17.2 percent of the 
nation's gross national product in 1992, the highest level of 
any major Asian country that year, according to data made public 
recently by the International Monetary Fund. 
  IMF tallies show that government-consumption expenditure 
rates in all other major Asian countries were below 10 percent 
in 1992, except in South Korea, where the rate was 11.4 percent. 
Singapore and Indonesia had 9.6 percent rates, and Hong Kong an 
8.6 percent rate. 
  Government-consumption expenditures include spending on 
personnel, office equipment, rent, and payouts on debts. 
  Government officials said the 17.2 percent was bloated by 
the 
10 percent of GNP spent on personnel. Personnel spending in 
Japan and South Korea was 6 percent and 4 percent, respectively, 
in 1992. 
  They said that spending on 700,000 government officials, 
half 
million-strong army, public schoolteachers, and on retired 
government employees' pensions added greatly to the governmet's 
burden. 
  The huge spending on personnel not only is a waste of the 
nation's limited resources, but also reduces government 
effectiveness, they warned. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

