<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Macao </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Interviews Portuguese Prime Minister on Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Interviews Portuguese Prime Minister on Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2004113394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1039 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2004113394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Macao, April 20 (XINHUA) -- Portuguese Prime 
Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva said that his recent visit to China 
was a great success. 
  In a special interview with XINHUA before he left Macao, 
Cavaco Silva said while in Beijing he exchanged views with 
leading Chinese leaders on the current Sino-Portuguese political 
and economic relations, as well as matters relating to Macao, 
adding both sides were happy with good bilateral political 
relations and agreed to strengthen contact in economic and trade 
fields. 
  The Portuguese prime minister also said on Macao issue, both 
sides held that it was necessary to maintain Macao's stability 
and economic development through dialogue between the 
governments of China and Portugal. 
  During his visit in Beijing, Silva said, a loan agreement 
involving 200 million U.S. dollars was signed to support 
Portuguese exports and investment in China, and his entourage of 
over 60 Portuguese businessmen had wide contacts with Chinese 
enterpreneurs, noting that these have laid a foundation for the 
development of economic and trade relations between the two 
countries. 
  Silva also praised the rapid economic development on China's 
mainland, saying it should be attributed to the reform and 
opening policies launched by the Chinese leaders and the 
enterprising spirit of the Chinese people. 
  On Macao issue, Silva again stressed the importance of 
dialogue and cooperation between the two countries, adding it 
would guarantee the settlement of matters relating to the 
transition in Macao. 
  He eventually said, the Portuguese Government, as will the 
Chinese side, would make all-out efforts to maintain the 
stability and progress in Macao. 

</TEXT>

