<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Clinton To Unveil New Bosnia Strategy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Clinton To Unveil New Bosnia Strategy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2004165994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1537 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2004165994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, April 20 (XINHUA) -- President Bill 
Clinton will announce details of a new U.S. plan on Bosnia later 
today, the White House said. 
  "We have new military and diplomatic initiatives which the 
President will likely discuss later today," White House 
spokeswoman Dee Dee Myers said. 
  Clinton met twice with his national security advisers for 
some four hours Tuesday [19 April] on how to deal with the 
worsening situation in Bosnia, especially in the encircled 
Bosnian Muslim enclave of Gorazde. 
  It was reported that the U.S. plan included the support of 
wider use of air power against the Bosnia Serbs, not only in the 
six U.N.-authorized "safe areas" for the Muslims but on other 
Serb strategic positions. 
  The plan also called for tougher economic sanctions against 
the Serb republic, seen by the West as supporter of the Bosnian 
Serbs in perpetuating the two-year war. 
  In Brussels, NATO officials discussed the wider use of air 
power on Bosnia but no final decision was reached. 
  Analysts believe that little objection will be expected to 
stiffer sanctions on Serbia but the military moves might 
encounter differences because many European countries have 
troops on the ground in Bosnia and their governments fear Serb 
retaliations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

