<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Hata as Candidate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Hata as Candidate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2204094794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0900 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2204094794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 22 (XINHUA) -- Japan's ruling coalition 
party leaders today formally chose Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata 
as candidate to succeed out-going Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa, who abruptly announced his resignation two weeks ago. 
  At a meeting this afternoon, the leaders endorsed a policy 
platform for a new cabinet and named Hata as the coalition's 
joint candidate for the prime ministerial election in both 
houses of the Diet (parliament) that is expected to meet next 
Monday, coalition officials said. 
  Hata, 58, concurrently the deputy prime minister in the 
Hosokawa cabinet, is expected to win the premiership election 
because of the coalition's majority status in the Diet. 
  Soon after the election, Hata, who is the leader of 
Shinseito 
(Japan Renewal Party) which is the coalition's core party, is 
expected to launch his new administration, the officials said. 
  The endorsement of Hata came after secretaries general of 
the 
ruling parties struck a deal early today on two key issues -- 
tax system reform and Japan's response to the suspected nuclear 
development program on the Korean peninsula. 
  The agreement put an end to two weeks of feud, first over 
the 
procedures for picking Hosokawa's successor and then over the 
above- mentioned two issues, which are crucial to keeping the 
nine-month-old alliance intact. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

