<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Holds Weekly News Briefing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Holds Weekly News Briefing </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Comments on Li Peng's Central Asia Visit </H4>

<F P=102> OW2104090394 Beijing XINHUA in English 0849 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2104090394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 21 (XINHUA) -- The current visits by 
Chinese Premier Li Peng to four Central Asian countries are by 
no means directed against any other country, Chinese Foreign 
Ministry spokesman Wu Jianmin said here this afternoon. 
  Wu was addressing a weekly press conference, at which he 
denied a report that Li's visit was aimed at contending with 
Russia for influence in the countries of the Commonwealth of 
Independent States. 
  The spokesman said that the Chinese premier's visits are 
return visits for those made by the leaders of the countries in 
question, and the purpose is to enhance mutual understanding 
with these countries, and promote good-neighborly friendship, as 
well as develop mutually beneficial co-operation. 
  "Therefore, the visits are by no means directed against any 
other country," Wu said. 
  "The friendly co-operation in various fields between China 
and Russia is developing steadily." 
  He went on: "We are keen to see the continued development of 
the friendship between Russia and the Central Asian countries, 
which are neighbors of both China and Russia." 

</TEXT>

