<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Owen Arrives in Moscow on To Discuss Bosnian Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Owen Arrives in Moscow on To Discuss Bosnian Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2004213094 Beijing XINHUA in English 2026 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2004213094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, April 20 (XINHUA) -- Lord David Owen, co- 
chairman of the Coordination Committee of the International 
Conference on Yugoslavia, arrived here from London on Wednesday 
[20 April] to discuss with Russia on its participation in the 
Bosnian issue. 
  Thorvald Stoltenberg, another co-chairman of the conference, 
is expected to arrive later. 
  The two international mediators are scheduled to have talks 
with Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev on Russia's 
participation in adopting political resolutions on the war-torn 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, one of the six former Yugoslav republics. 
  Before his departure from London, Lord Owen said Russia 
should not only take part in drawing a chart dividing 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and attend talks on lifting sanctions against 
the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, but also join the adoption 
resolutions on what military actions should be carried out by 
the world community in this area, according to the ITAR-TASS 
NEWS AGENCY. 
  On Tuesday, Kozyrev told a news conference: "I would 
strongly 
recommend the Serb side not to try patience of the international 
community." 
  His deputy Vitaly Churkin said on Wednesday that "all Serbs 
(in Bosnia-Herzegovina) are on the brink of catastrophe, which 
may have grave consequences for the world." 
  Moscow's recent tough statements on Bosnian Serbs should not 
be viewed as backtracking on its previous policy, Churkin said, 
adding that "if Serbs find strength to turn to peace," Russia 
will continue acting as a "channel of communication between 
Serbs and the world community." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

