<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pakistani Troops May Be Deployed in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pakistani Troops May Be Deployed in Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2004165894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1513 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2004165894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Islamabad, April 20 (XINHUA) -- The deployment of 
Pakistani troops in Bosnia-Herzegovina will be possible by the 
end of June, said a Foreign Office spokesman here today. 
  Pakistan has decided to provide 3,000 troops for deployment 
in Bosnia-Herzegovina in response to U.N. Security Council 
Resolution 836 designed to protect six safe areas there. 
  The Pakistani troops, whose equipment supply is arranged by 
the United Nations from Germany, will be deployed in Bosnia 
under U.N. auspices. 
  Speaking at the weekly press briefing, the spokesman also 
informed journalists that Pakistan has moved a resolution in the 
U.N. Security Council seeking use of air strikes against Serbian 
artillery shelling on Gorazde. 
  The resolution also demands the withdrawal of the Serbian 
forces behind the line drawn when Gorazde was declared safe area 
and lifting of arms embargo against Bosnian forces, he said. 
  "The resolution was moved in light of Serbian aggression 
against the safe area of Gorazde," he added. 

</TEXT>

