<F P=100> Southeast Asia &amp; Pacific </F>
<H3> <TI>   Philippine Senator Praises Role in DPRK Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Philippine Senator Praises Role in DPRK Nuclear Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2104130394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1254 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2104130394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Manila, April 21 (XINHUA) -- China has earned 
world-wide appreciation for helping prevent the crisis in the 
Korean peninsula from further deteriorating, Senator Blas F. 
Ople said here today. 
  Ople, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, 
said that as he welcomed the Foreign Affairs Committee 
delegation of the National People's Congress of China at the 
Ninoy Aquino International Airport. 
  He said to a great extent it was due to China's efforts that 
the threat level to peace between the two Koreas has apparently 
now subsided. 
  The senator, who just returned from Marrakesh, Morroco, 
where 
97 nations signed the final act of the Uruguay Round of talks on 
the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT), said various 
delegations assembled in Marrakesh favored the early admission 
of China to GATT to be an original member of the new World Trade 
Organization (WTO), expected to succeed GATT by January 1995. 
  The WTO, to be credible, needs to be universal, and that 
standard cannot be attained without the admission of China, Ople 
said. 
  Zhu Liang, head of the Chinese parliamentary delegation, 
said 
Philippine-Chinese relations were a stabilizing influence in the 
East Asia region. 

</TEXT>

